  "prompt": "What is the difference between a grade of A+ and an A at the University of Illinois?",
  "response": "At the University of Illinois, the grading system primarily utilizes letter grades such as A, A\u2011, B+, B\u2011, and so on. **The university does not officially use an A\u207a grade** in its standard grading scale. Instead, the highest attainable grade is an **A**, which typically corresponds to a 4.0 grade point in the GPA calculation.\n\nHere are some key points regarding the grading system:\n\n- **A (4.0 GPA):** Represents excellent performance and is the highest standard grade awarded.\n- **A\u2011 (3.7 GPA):** Indicates very good performance, slightly below the top tier.\n\n**No A\u207a Grade:**\n- The absence of an A\u207a grade means that there's no distinction between an A and an A\u207a in terms of GPA or academic standing.\n- Transcripts will reflect an A as the highest grade without the need for an A\u207a designation.\n\n**Departmental Variations:**\n- While the general university grading policy does not include an A\u207a, it's always a good idea to verify if specific departments or programs have unique grading criteria. However, such instances are uncommon.\n\n**Impact on GPA:**\n- Since A\u207a is not part of the standard grading system at the University of Illinois, both A and A\u207a would effectively be treated the same way, typically as a 4.0 in GPA calculations.\n\n**Recommendation:**\n- For the most accurate and detailed information, consult the [University of Illinois' official grading policies](https://www.illinois.edu/) or contact your academic advisor or department directly.\n\nUnderstanding the grading system ensures you have clear expectations and can effectively plan your academic goals at the University of Illinois.",
